The Programme Officer, The Inclusion Project (TIP), Eniola Tikare, has called on govern­ments in the country to provide no-cost supply of menstrual hy­giene products to women and girls to enable them maintain good hygiene practices during their monthly circle. In a statement to mark this year’s World Day on Menstru­al Hygiene which takes place every May 27,Tikare stressed the need for government at all levels to support the female folk in rural areas and correctional facilities with feminine men­strual products. According to the statement, more significant population of Nigerians suffer from extreme poverty and majority are wom­en and girls within their men­suration age. -Advertisement- TIP believed that access to feminine products is a ba­sic right that allows all to live with dignity. It also stated that no women and girls should be allowed to face the health risks associated with improvising menstrual hygiene supplies. To mark the 2022 World’s Day on Menstrual Hygiene, TIP in the release said it do­nated several cartons of men­strual products to women in Kirikiri Custodial Centre and diapers for women with chil­dren in detention. In addition, it conducted a sensitisation programme on menstrual hygiene manage­ment to provide information from experts on menstrual hygiene management and menstrual rights. While stating that it would carry out a similar activity in other earmarked correctional center, TIP revealed that they are also raising awareness on menstrual hygiene manage­ment among school girls and women in Imo and Kano State. TIP, therefore, appealed to governments to provide ac­cess to clean and accessible water and other basic facili­ties in schools and custodial facilities, saying that women in detention should have ad­equate water supply, access to sufficient clean water and soap to enable better hygiene practices, while prison in­frastructure should be such that it ensures the privacy and dignity of menstruating inmates.